Ta Prohm Temple, Angkor, Cambodia - Traveling Mark|https://www.travelingmark.com/cambodia/ta-prohm-temple-angkor-cambodia/|According to the inscription on the foundation stele, Ta Prohm was consecrated in 1186 AD. Originally named Rajavihara (Royal Temple), Ta Prohm was one of the first temples with which the god king Jayavarman VII embarked on its immense mission of temple building. The sanskrit inscription also provides colorful details about how impressive Ta Prohm must have been during its time. From it the archaeologists learned that the temple housed the following: - 512 Silk Beds - 523 Parasols - 867 Veils from China - 40,620 Pearls - 4,540 Precious Stones - 35 Diamonds  ...    Whether these numbers truly reflected the content of the temple grounds or were vastly exaggerated to make king Jayavarman VII larger than life is left for speculations. As for the population in and around Ta Prohm, the inscription tells us that the temple was home to the following: - 79,365 Total Maintenance Staff - 2,202 Assistants - 2,740 Officials - 615 Apsara Dancers - 18 High Priests  ...    Prajnaparamita (the
